expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>527</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i-9</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i-9.xml</fr:route><fr:number>9</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-i</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> be the unit disc, <fr:tex>D^*=D \setminus \{ 0 \}</fr:tex>, and <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>
  <fr:tex
display="block">      \begin {CD}       X @&gt;&gt;&gt;  \mathbb {P} ^r( \mathbb {C} ) \times  D      \\ @VfVV @VV \mathrm {pr}_2V      \\ D @= D      \end {CD}   </fr:tex>
  a family of projective varieties parameterised by <fr:tex>D</fr:tex>, with <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> proper, and <fr:tex>f|D^*</fr:tex> smooth.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  Keeping the notation of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.xml"
number="8"></fr:ref>, and recalling that, in the analogy between Henselian traits and small neighbourhoods of <fr:tex>0</fr:tex> in the complex line, we have the following dictionary (note that the spectrum of the ring of germs at <fr:tex>0</fr:tex> of holomorphic functions is a Henselian trait):
</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>333</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Dictionary</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-i-dictionary-9.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-i-dictionary-9.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>9.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-i-9</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:table
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>D</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>\operatorname {Spec} (V)</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>D^*</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>\operatorname {Spec} (K)</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td>a universal covering <fr:tex>\widetilde {D^*}</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>D^*</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>\operatorname {Spec} ( \overline {K})</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td>the fundamental group <fr:tex>\pi _1(D^*)</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td>the inertia group <fr:tex>I</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td>(with <fr:tex>\pi _1(D^*)= \mathbb {Z} \simeq \mathbb {Z} (1)_ \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>)</html:td>
      <html:td>(with <fr:tex>I_l= \mathbb {Z} _l(1)</fr:tex>)</html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>X</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td>a projective scheme <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> over <fr:tex>\operatorname {Spec} (V)</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>X^*=f^{-1}(D^*)</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>X_K</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>\widetilde {X}=X \times _D \widetilde {D^*}</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>X_{ \overline {K}}</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td>the local system <fr:tex>R^if_* \mathbb {Z} |D^*</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td>the Galois module <fr:tex>H^i(X_{ \overline {K}}, \mathbb {Z} _l)</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td><fr:tex>H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Z} )</fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex>H^i(X_{ \overline {K}}, \mathbb {Z} _l)</fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:table></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>
  Note that <fr:tex>\widetilde {X}</fr:tex> is homotopically equivalent to each of the fibres <fr:tex>X_t=f^{-1}(t)</fr:tex> (for <fr:tex>t \in  D^*</fr:tex>): <fr:tex>H^i(X_{ \overline {K}}, \mathbb {Z} _l)</fr:tex> is again analogous to <fr:tex>H^i(X_t, \mathbb {Z} )</fr:tex>, and the transformation of the monodromy <fr:tex>T</fr:tex> corresponds to the action of <fr:tex>I</fr:tex>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  Here, again, we know that a subgroup of finite index of <fr:tex>\pi _1(D^*)</fr:tex> acts unipotently on <fr:tex>H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Q} )=H^i(X_t, \mathbb {Q} )</fr:tex>.
  We place ourselves in the semi-stable case, where all of <fr:tex>\pi _1(D^*)</fr:tex> acts unipotently (this reduces to replacing <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> by a finite covering), and let <fr:tex>T</fr:tex> be the action of the canonical generator of <fr:tex>\pi _1(D^*)</fr:tex>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  By <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-3"
href="hodge-theory-i-3.xml"
number="3"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.xml"
number="8"></fr:ref>, we expect for <fr:tex>H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Q} ) \simeq  H^i(X_t, \mathbb {Q} )</fr:tex> to be endowed with an increasing filtration <fr:tex>W</fr:tex>, for <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _n^W(H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Q} ))</fr:tex> to be endowed with a Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex>n</fr:tex>, for <fr:tex>\log  T(W_n) \subset  W_{n-2}</fr:tex>, and for <fr:tex>\log  T</fr:tex> to induce a morphism of Hodge structures
  <fr:tex
display="block">     M_n \colon   \mathbb {Z} (-1) \otimes \operatorname {Gr} _n^W(H^i)      \to   \operatorname {Gr} _{n-2}^W(H^i).   </fr:tex>
  We would further like for <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8.2"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.2.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="8.2"></fr:ref>, and not just <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8.3"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.3.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="8.3"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8.4"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.4.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="8.4"></fr:ref>, to have an analogue.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  We have in fact managed to define, for each vector <fr:tex>u</fr:tex> of the tangent space to <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> at <fr:tex>\{ 0 \}</fr:tex>, a mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex>\mathscr {H}_u</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Z} )</fr:tex>.
  The filtration <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> and the Hodge structures on the <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _n^W(H^i)</fr:tex> are independent of <fr:tex>u</fr:tex>, and the dependence on <fr:tex>u</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>\mathscr {H}_u</fr:tex> can be expressed simply in terms of <fr:tex>T</fr:tex>.
  
  Analogously to <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8.2"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.2.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="8.2"></fr:ref>, we find that, for any <fr:tex>u</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>\log  T</fr:tex> induces a homomorphism of mixed Hodge structures
  <fr:tex
display="block">     M \colon   \mathbb {Z} (1) \otimes  H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Z} )      \to  H^i( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Z} ).   </fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p>
  Finally, the analogy in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i-8.5"
href="hodge-theory-i-8.5.xml"
number="8.5"></fr:ref> is not misleading (but here, the fact that <fr:tex>f|D^*</fr:tex> is assumed to be proper and smooth is probably essential).
  We can prove that
  <fr:tex
display="block">     ( \log  T)^k \colon   \operatorname {Gr} _{n+k}^W(H^n( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Q} ))      \to   \operatorname {Gr} _{n-k}^W(H^n( \widetilde {X}, \mathbb {Q} ))   </fr:tex>
  is an isomorphism for all <fr:tex>k</fr:tex> (cf. [<fr:link
href="W1958.xml"
type="local"
addr="W1958">W1958</fr:link>, IV 6, Corollary to Theorem 5]).
  This characterises the filtration <fr:tex>W</fr:tex>.
  Until now, we have only had an analogue of the positivity theorem of Hodge (cf. [<fr:link
href="W1958.xml"
type="local"
addr="W1958">W1958</fr:link>, IV 7, Corollary to Theorem 7]) in very particular cases.
  We hope that the mixed structures <fr:tex>\mathscr {H}_u</fr:tex> determine the asymptotic behaviour, for <fr:tex>t \to0</fr:tex>, of the family of pure structures <fr:tex>H^i(X, \mathbb {Z} )</fr:tex> (for <fr:tex>t \in  D^*</fr:tex>).
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks></fr:backlinks><fr:references></fr:references></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>